(10, 1, '2019-06-13 14:18:15', '2019-06-13 13:18:15', '<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><em>Abstract</em>—The purpose of this paper is to identify a\nnew model for team formation and roles during the software development process\nusing Emotional intelligence indicators, especially the personalities type\nusing MBTI test. The first section of the paper we have identified all the\ndefinitions and the myth around emotional intelligence and why is it important\nduring the next ten years.&nbsp; We also\nmentioned all the effects of the emotional intelligence on careers and\nrecruitment field with big companies such as Google, Apple, and Oracle and how\nthese companies change the industry with their interviews. In the final section\nwe propose the model that we suggest to work within the team formation process.\nIn this model we try to demonstrate all personates advantages and disadvantages\nfrom the MBTI test and how can these results reflect on the team formation. Also\nwe talked about the future work to this paper, we hope to continue and create\nnew MBTI test customized to the workers in the IT field (developers, Managers,\ntechnical support, quality assurance) by building this we will have a new\naccurate model to measure Emotional intelligence in the software development\nindustry can really change the interviews and help companies and workers to\nfind the best jobs and the best roles with their personalities.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Keywords—Emotional Intelligence(EQ), Intelligence quotient\n(IQ).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5><strong>Acknowledgment</strong></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This paper is the final paper for Managing Software\nDevelopment course in Innopolis University first semester in Master program in\nsoftware engineering 2018/2019.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I want to say special thanks for: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Prof. Andrey Sadovykh for all effort that you put with us all the\nsemester and for your interesting way to demonstrate things.</li><li>TAs. Evgeny, Oleg and Ildar for your time and effort with us and your\nsupport for me to improve my works. </li><li>&nbsp;All Innopolis University Team for\ngood hospitality and kindness.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nI.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Introduction </strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Recently, the job\nreview site Glassdoor compiled a list of 15 different companies that don’t\nrequire job applicants to have college degrees. The list includes high-paying\ntech outlets like Apple, Google, and IBM, in addition to service-oriented\ncompanies like Costco, Starbucks, and Chipotle [9]. After this\nannouncement,&nbsp;everybody starts to realize that the degree is not important\nto get hired in the biggest companies in the world, and the question now “what\nare the new factors the big companies concentrate on when they do the hiring\nprocess?”.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is two\nimportant factor in the current world controlled the hiring process, first; the\ntechnical skill set, which means the experience that employees get from doing\ntasks in his job, also the main skill that companies pay for the employees to\ndo every day. Second; Soft skills, also defined as “combination of people\nskills, social skills, communication skills, character traits, attitudes,\ncareer attribute, social intelligence, and emotional intelligence quotients\namong others that enable people to navigate their environment, work well with\nothers, perform well, and achieve their goals with complementing hard skills”\n[10].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Now both of these\nfactors are the main metrics to evaluate employees, but the second factor is\nmore important than the first. let\'s see it from a different point of\nview,&nbsp;for example:&nbsp; In a 2017 report\n[11], Deloitte Access Economics predicted that “soft skill-intensive\noccupations will account for two-thirds of all jobs by 2030, compared to half\nof all jobs in 2000. The number of jobs in soft-skill intensive occupations is\nexpected to grow at 2.5 times the rate of jobs in other occupations.”.\n&nbsp;Also all job interviews with companies like Google, Microsoft and Oracle\nfocus on interview questions about soft skills and how to deal with the\nsituation. Also, it happened that during an interview, an applicant has not\nbeen asked any single programming question and he was applying to be an oracle\nDevOps [12].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the previous\nparagraphs, we conclude that the soft skill now is more important than the hard\nskills or the technical skills, and the bigger players in the market now such\nas (Google, IBM, Oracle ...etc.) &nbsp;looking for talents and skills but you\nshould pass the critical test of soft skills.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this paper we\nwill try to focus on part of the soft skills called “Emotional intelligence”\nand dig in the depth to answers some questions:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>What is “Emotional\n     intelligence”?</li><li>Why EQ is more important\n     than IQ? </li><li>How “Emotional\n     intelligence” related to the software engineering?</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Why “Emotional\n     intelligence” take a lot of hype and everyone talking about it now? </li><li>Which part of “Emotional\n     intelligence” is essential for IT people?</li><li>How can we measure\n     “Emotional intelligence”? </li><li>Which cases that\n     “Emotional intelligence” doesn’t work well?</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After answering\nthese questions, we will make our conclusion about why “Emotional intelligence”\nis essential in the IT field especially “team formation and building”, and how\ncan educate your team about it and teach them to develop this skill and using\nit, also how to make the technical skills that they have more valuable.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What is Emotional Intelligence? </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emotional\nIntelligence (EI) concept has&nbsp;become a very important indicator of a\nperson ‘s &nbsp;&nbsp;knowledge,&nbsp;skills and abilities in\nworkplace, school and person life. The overall result of research\'s suggest\nthat EI plays a significant role in the job performance, motivation, decision\nmaking,&nbsp;successful management, and leadership. Thus applying EI\nmethodology in higher education can have lots of benefits for students.\n&nbsp;It not only fulfills their desire but also makes them more efficient in\ntheir field” [13].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The roots of\nemotional intelligence were traced by Darwin\'s early work on the importance of\nemotional expression survival. In the 1900s, even though traditional\ndefinitions of intelligence emphasized cognitive aspects such as memory and\nproblem solving later on several researchers in the intelligence field of study\nhad begun to be aware of the importance of the non-cognitive aspects. When\npsychologists began to think and write about intelligence, they focused on\ncognitive aspects, such as memory and problem -solving, However, there were\nresearchers who understand that the non-cognitive aspects were also important\nin intelligence [13].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Before emotional\nintelligence people used term “social intelligence” to describe the skill of\nunderstanding and managing other people, also it was very important skills to\nget a good job; because it constructs how to organize people and these are\ntasks for management and role of the management always more important than any\njob.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Officially\npsychologists John Mayer and Peter Salovey introduced the concept of emotional\nintelligence in the early 1990s. according to them, emotions are internal\nevents that coordinate physiological responses, cognitions, and conscious\nawareness. They define emotional intelligence as, “The ability to perceive\nemotions, to access and generate emotions so as to assist thought, to\nunderstand emotions and emotional knowledge,&nbsp;and to regulate emotions\nreflectively so as to promote emotional and intellectual growth” [14].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What is Intelligence quotient?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Intelligence\nquotient is a score derived from one of several standardized tests designed to\nassess intelligence, also its the ability to learn, understand and apply\ninformation to skills, logical reasoning, word comprehension, math skills,\nabstract and spatial thinking, filter irrelevant information. It is lead to\nsuccess with challenging tasks, ability to analyze and connect the dots,\nresearch, and development in the workplace, also it can be measured using tests\nsuch as Stanford-Binet test; Wechsler; Woodcock-Johnson Tests of Cognitive\nAbilities [16].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What\'s More Important — IQ or EQ?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Today, scores on\nmost IQ tests are calculated by comparing the test taker\'s score to the scores\nof other people in the same age group, IQ represents abilities such as Visual\nand spatial processing, Knowledge of the world, Fluid reasoning, Working\nmemory, and short-term memory, Quantitative Reasoning. On the other hand, EQ is\na measure of a person\'s level of emotional intelligence. This refers to a\nperson\'s ability to perceive, control, evaluate, and express emotions.\nResearchers such as John Mayer and Peter Salovey as well as writers like Daniel\nGoleman have helped shine a light on emotional intelligence, making it a hot\ntopic in areas ranging from business management to education. EQ is centered on\nabilities such as, identifying emotions, evaluating how others feel,\ncontrolling one\'s own emotions, perceiving how others feel, using emotions to\nfacilitate social communication, Relating to others [17].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Some critics\nbegan to realize that not only was high intelligence no guarantee for success\nin life, it was also perhaps too narrow a concept to fully encompass the wide\nrange of human abilities and knowledge. IQ is still recognized as an important\nelement of success, particularly when it comes to academic achievement. People\nwith high IQs typically to do well in school, often earn more money, and ten to\nbe healthier in general. But today experts recognize it is not the only\ndeterminate of life success. Instead, it is part of a complex array of\ninfluences that includes emotional intelligence among other things. The concept\nof emotional intelligence has had a strong impact in a number of areas,\nincluding the business world. Many companies now mandate emotional intelligence\ntraining and utilize EQ tests as part of the hiring process [17].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>D.&nbsp;&nbsp; Why Emotional intelligence is hyped?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to Grant,\na professor at the University of Pennsylvania’s Wharton School of Business,\n“When you’re good at controlling your own emotions, you can disguise your true\nfeelings.” He goes on to say that leaders with selfish motives can use their\nmastery of emotion as weapons for manipulating others. “The results,” he says,\n“can be devastating.” Besides having a decidedly dark side, you might be\nsurprised to learn some facts that proponents of this popular fad tend to omit\nfrom their enthusiastic and motivational books, speeches, and coaching sessions\n[18].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Broad claims\nlinking emotional intelligence to everything from leadership performance and\nbusiness success to reduced stress and personal happiness are simply untrue. A\nrecent comprehensive meta-analysis published in the Journal of Applied\nPsychology showed absolutely no broad correlation between emotional\nintelligence and job performance [18].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>And claims that\nCEOs, executives and business leaders with high EQs are more successful are\nsimply ludicrous. Consider some of the most highly accomplished entrepreneurs\nof our time: Steve Jobs, Bill Gates, Andy Grove, Larry Ellison, Larry Page,\nMark Zuckerberg and Elon Musk. I’d be surprised to find an ounce of emotional\nintelligence among them. Granted, we also have Richard Branson, John Mackey and Tony Hsieh,\nbut that’s the whole point. People are remarkably diverse. There are lots of\ndifferent ways to become a highly accomplished leader, enjoy a successful\ncareer and build a great company. And emotional intelligence is by no means a\npredictor of any of those things [18].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Co-author of\nEmotional Intelligence 2.0 Travis Bradberry claims that 90% of top performers\nhave high emotional intelligence. His EQ testing suggests that these successful\npeople are somehow capable of avoiding nearly every human behavioral flaw. They\ndon’t compare themselves with others, dig in their heels, have pessimistic\nthoughts, dwell on failure, lose perspective, hang around negative people, lose\nsleep or hold grudges [18].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One of the\nprincipal tenets of emotional-intelligence proponents is that awareness leads\nto behavioral change. They suggest that by reading a book, taking a test or\ngoing to a seminar you become more aware of your emotions and that, with\npractice, you will become a better leader and more successful at work. If that were the case – if it were really that simple –\npeople would not need years of therapy, hard work and discipline to change\ntheir behavior. Simple awareness would enable all of us to stamp out our\nself-destructive tendencies and avoid all the pitfalls that make us less happy and successful than we perhaps\ncould be in a perfect world [18].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To conclude, yes\nemotional intelligence has a lot of hype now and everybody will look cool when\nthey talk about it, but in fact this skill need a lot of hard work too and it\'s\nnot something you can learn in one day, the hype that take emotional\nintelligence to a place to make it as solution for every problem; but it\'s not,\nit is a set of skill will help everyone to improve themselves to have a good\nimpact on the others. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>E.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Emotional Intelligence Models </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we\nmentioned&nbsp;\"the ability to monitor one\'s own and other people\'s\nemotions, to discriminate between different emotions and label them\nappropriately, and to use emotional information to guide thinking and behavior\"\nby Peter Salovey and John Mayer. This definition was later broken down and\nrefined into four proposed abilities: perceiving, using, understanding, and\nmanaging emotions for emotional intelligence [14].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are three\nmain models of emotional intelligence: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Ability model</li><li>Mixed model</li><li>Trait model</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <strong>ability\nmodel</strong> defined by “the capacity to reason about emotions, and of emotions,\nto enhance thinking. It includes the abilities to accurately perceive emotions,\nto access and generate emotions so as to assist thought, to understand emotions\nand emotional knowledge, and to reflectively regulate emotions so as to promote\nemotional and intellectual growth”, also it has four type of abilities\nPerceiving emotions: the ability to detect and decipher emotions in faces,\npictures, voices, and cultural artifacts. Using emotions: the ability to\nharness emotions to facilitate various cognitive activities, such as thinking\nand problem-solving. Understanding emotions: the ability to comprehend emotion\nlanguage and to appreciate complicated relationships among emotions. Managing\nemotions: the ability to regulate emotions in both ourselves and in others\n[28].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <strong>mixed model</strong>\ndefined by “The capacity for recognizing our own feelings and those of others,\nfor motivating ourselves, and for managing emotions well in ourselves and in\nour relationships”, and it has five main categories:\n-Self-awareness: the ability\nto know one\'s emotions, strengths, weaknesses, drives, values and goals and\nrecognize their impact on others while using gut feelings to guide decisions.\nSelf-regulation: involves controlling or redirecting one\'s disruptive emotions\nand impulses and adapting to changing circumstances. Social skill: managing\nrelationships to move people in the desired direction. Empathy: considering\nother people\'s feelings especially when making decisions. Motivation: being\ndriven to achieve for the sake of achievement [29].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The <strong>Trait\nmodel</strong>, it is coming from trait theory defined by “study of human\npersonality” and the trait model is “constellation of emotional\nself-perceptions located at the lower levels of personality” [30].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>F.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Emotional Intelligence Models Measurement</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ability model can\nbe measured by “Mayer and Salovey\'s model of Emotional intelligence”, the\nMayer-Salovey-Caruso Emotional Intelligence Test (MSCEIT) is based on a series\nof emotion-based problem-solving items. Consistent with the model\'s claim of EI\nas a type of intelligence, the test is modeled on ability-based IQ tests. By\ntesting a person\'s abilities on each of the four branches of emotional intelligence,\nit generates scores for each of the branches as well as a total score [31]. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are some\nmeasures can improve the ability in emotional intelligence like [32]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Diagnostic Analysis of Nonverbal Accuracy:&nbsp; The Adult Facial version includes 24\n     photographs of an equal amount of happy, sad, angry, and fearful facial\n     expressions of both high and low intensities which are balanced by gender,\n     the tasks of the participants is to answer which of the four emotions is\n     present in the given stimuli.</li><li>Japanese and Caucasian Brief Affect Recognition\n     test:&nbsp; Participants try to identify\n     56 faces of Caucasian and Japanese individuals expressing seven emotions\n     such happiness, contempt, disgust, sadness, anger, surprise, and fear,\n     which may also trail off for 0.2 seconds to a different emotion.</li><li>Levels of Emotional Awareness Scale: Participants reads\n     26 social scenes and answers their anticipated feelings and continuum of\n     low to high emotional awareness.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The mixed model\ncan be measured by Two measurement tools are based on the Goleman model [29]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The Emotional Competence Inventory (ECI), which was\n     created in 1999, and the Emotional and Social Competency Inventory (ESCI),\n     a newer edition of the ECI was developed in 2007. The Emotional and Social\n     Competency – University Edition (ESCI-U) is also available. These tools\n     developed by Goleman and Boyatzis provide a behavioral measure of the\n     Emotional and Social Competencies.</li><li>The Emotional Intelligence Appraisal, which was created\n     in 2001 and which can be taken as a self-report or 360-degree assessment</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For the trait\nmodel there a lot of studies to measure emotional intelligence in the mode such\nas [33]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The EQ-i 2.0 is a self-report measure designed to\n     measure a number of constructs related to EI, originally known as the\n     BarOn EQ-i.</li><li>TEIQue provides an operationalization for the model of\n     Petrides and colleagues, that conceptualizes EI in terms of personality.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are some\ntools and test and studies and models suggested to measure emotional\nintelligence, all these model have a specific point of view and can be used in\nspecific terms. &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nII.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>&nbsp;RELATED WORK</strong><strong></strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There is a lot of\nstudies talking about emotional intelligence, the challenge was to find studies\nsupport our approach, using emotional intelligence indicators with team\nformation. From our research we can classified studies to categories: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Studies about Emotional intelligence\n     indicators in a different environment such as (Work, Academic life\n     ...etc.) </li><li>Studies about correlation between\n     leadership roles and emotional intelligence.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the first category, we have a study\nmade by G. Latha, N. Panchanatham, John William Felix from Annamalai University\nin India about \"Stress and Emotional Intelligence:&nbsp; A Study among Software Professionals in\nChennai \". The study identifies the impact of emotional intelligence on\nstress experienced by software professionals.&nbsp;\nPrimary data were collected from 200 software professionals working in\nChennai, the state capital of Tamilnadu, India. Stress is measured using the\nOccupational&nbsp;&nbsp; Stress Index scale\ndeveloped by Srivastava and Singh.&nbsp;&nbsp;\nEmotional Intelligence Is measured using Emotional Intelligence Scale\nDeveloped by Bar-On. The results prove that emotional intelligence has an\nimpact on the stress experienced. All the dimensions of emotional intelligence\nare found to be influencing the dimensions of stress. Many types of research\nhave proved that emotional intelligence can be developed. So the training\nmodules on stress management can incorporate emotional intelligence as a part\n[20]. In the second category, we have two ways to represent the correlation\nbetween leadership and emotional intelligence, direct and indirect. For the\ndirect way, we have this study “emotional intelligence and leadership” by Suciu\nSorin and Vasile Gherhes form \" Polytechnic University of Timisoara\".\nThe study talked about how to discover the overwhelming economic potential of\nthese human qualities unjustly ignored, while providing a synopsis of emotional\ncompetencies whose presence in the leadership is one of the most important\nresources of a company, also show the importance of emotional skills for those\nwho occupy positions of responsibility because it is their task to get the\nmaximum benefits from the employees [21]. On the other hand, we have the\nindirect way that studies use to correlate between leadership and emotional\nintelligence indicators, for example, we have this study by Daniel Goleman\n\"Leadership That Gets Results\". The study talked about how the most\nsuccessful leaders have strengths in the following emotional intelligence\ncompetencies: self-awareness, self-regulation, motivation, empathy, and social\nskill. There are six basic styles of leadership; each makes use of the key\ncomponents of emotional intelligence in different combinations. The best\nleaders don\'t know just one style of leadership they’re skilled at several and\nhave the flexibility to switch between styles as the circumstances dictate [2].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In this paper, we\nare trying to see how emotional intelligence help leaders with team formation\nand how they can increase the productivity in their team and in the work\nenvironment, also make the team feel comfortable with each other through the\nnew formation using emotional intelligence indicators.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nIII.&nbsp; </strong><strong>BODY &amp; ANALYSIS</strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Emotional Intelligence in Software Engineering</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The question will be asked; how emotional\nintelligence affect the process in software engineering? &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In fact, emotional intelligence focus on\nunderstanding the engineers developing software and discover is there any\nsignificant associations between the personalities of software engineers and\ntheir work preferences. So the relation between emotional intelligence and\nsoftware engineering or software development is related to the team and their\npersonalities and how they responded to each other in daily work, software\nengineers have their own zone that can be different than any work zone, their\ndaily routine is solving difficult puzzles and mysteries in code and they have\nan advantage with a deep understanding of logic, algorithms and rational\nbehavior. These conditions make the software engineers are a special employee\nwith a different mindset than any regular employees. Let\'s take a simple\nexample of how the software engineer think and how regular employee think? When\nsoftware engineer talks to his team “that contain three men and two ladies”,\nmaybe he will say “hey guys”, as software engineer this is like the “naming\nconvention- for example: let variable ‘A’ as integer” on the other hand some\npeoples see this as offensive action for gender for these ladies in the team,\nand if you try to convince that engineer to say “hey everyone” he will answer\nwith “it’s the same” it\'s just naming. So the problem start with their daily\njob and dealing with software as daily job make you make focus about logic and\nhow programming language think, this not like prediction from this myself this\nis a fact you can see it and feel it when you deal with people working with\nsoftware, for example in this study by Alan S. Horowitz “ Singing for\nThemselves”, he is talking about how some software engineers say to customers\ndirectly “you are stupid”[22], how in the world employee say this to customers\ndirectly in their faces, maybe the customer is stupid but it\'s not polite to\nsay that in their faces. Now we know how emotional intelligence connected to\nsoftware engineering and which the part that can affect the process of software\nengineering. The next section will talk about the Impact of emotional\nintelligence on developers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impact of Emotional intelligence in Developers</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the previous section, we saw how\nsoftware engineers think about the small things and how they reflect it, from\nthis point we will demonstrate how can be reflected a developer daily work.\nDevelopers are the main key of the software development, also they are the core\nof the talent in the companies, their work is the main product for software\ncompanies so the success of these companies can be measured by their skills and\ntalent. Also, the quality of service depends on their work, so companies have\nto find the best way to make them comfortable with their daily work and they\nmust have strategies to handle all the situations between them. Developers are\nsoftware engineering to they are filled with logic and judgmental mentality,\nthey deal with difficult algorithms and complex logic, these conditions make\nthem more realistic, also they are very smart; because their work makes them\nface these difficult issues every day. From this we can conclude that there is\nsome developer are prima donnas [22], they are arrogant and they think that\nthey always right, also they don\'t listen to anyone and they assume that they\nknow everything. The problem doesn\'t come from nowhere in the next sections\nthat talked about “Leadership and emotional intelligence” we will see the\ncauses of all this, but let\'s see how developers see the world of emotional\nintelligence? </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we said\nemotional intelligence as a short definition is “Managing feeling so that they\nare expressed appropriately and effectively\"[15], on the other hand,\ndevelopers always improve their technical skills without paying attention to\ntheir feeling and their coworkers feeling about anything, they always focus on\ntheir tasks.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As we mentioned in the beginning, now big\ncompanies in the market does not look only for talented, skilled developers,\nnow they are looking for developers with high emotional intelligence to fit\ntheir teams, these companies now look to developer from different perspectives\nsuch as self-management and their ability to control impulsive thoughts and\nbehaviors, manage emotions, and adapt to life’s surprises, also the&nbsp; social awareness that mean to understand the\nemotions, thoughts, and actions of others in various social settings or group\ninteractions, finally the self-awareness and how much you know about yourself\nand how to build awareness of our strengths, weaknesses, thoughts, and\nbehavior.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To conclude, yes\ndevelopers are the main key of the software development, their skills are the\nmost important asset for companies, so every company looking for the developer\ncan fit their teams and they can use their skills, and make them happy to\nachieve a win-win situation. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impact of Emotional Intelligence in Team chemistry</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>High-performance\nteams go beyond the design of specific work groups and teams. The\nhigh-performance team, as defined here, refers to a working system that\nemphasizes the deliberate integration of social and technical systems at work\n[4]. Every successful company claimed that they have a strong team. Teams are\nthe middle component of the companies, teams are a bunch of developers,\ntesters, and leaders, companies assigned them to a specific project, their task\nis to deliver a project in a specific period of time. As we say before,\ndevelopers are the core of the talent in companies and teams is the structure\nthat allows to developers to work together, from this perspective you will\nassume that “the developers in teams don\'t have any problems with dealing with\neach other”; because they working with each other and they have the same\nmentality, all of them are logical.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In fact, teams\nhave a lot of issues even they are a bunch of developers. Developers are human\nand as we said talented developer some of them are arrogant and don\'t have any\nsoft skills even when they think they are logical. For example: prima donna\'s\ndevelopers don\'t respect anyone who doesn\'t have the same amount of skills and\nknowledge, and we know that the team members are not the same in experience and\nseniority, so this can make line or layer between junior developers and senior\ndevelopers and this make conflict and effect on the chemistry of team.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emotional\nintelligence as skill try to improve the person as person and “how to\nunderstand the other\'s feelings”, also there is a big part of it cover\nrelationship management, and it’s mean how to develop positive relationships\nwith teams and how to communicate with them effectively, influence and\ncontribute to your groups, and manage conflict. These are the points emotional\nintelligence can give it to developers to make themselves better and fit any\nteam this lead to positive growth in their personalities and make them deal\nwith situations where conflict and difficulties arise and solve efficiently.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the beginning,\ndevelopers may think that emotional intelligence is an additional skill, “if\nyou have it you are good” and if not “it doesn\'t matter”. Nowadays the huge\npart of the development process is to motivate, influence, provide training and\ncoaching to other developers in teams, the major job of senior developers is\nnot creating magical code, their job is being role model and gives the space to\ntheir team member to think and discuss and learn. These mentalities can lead to\nincrease the ability to listen and more positive, thoughtful, and reasoned\nresponses to situations and to more interactive during the development process,\nalso to decrease stress between the team member and make the more initiative.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To conclude, team\nchemistry is depending on the main part any team and they are the senior\ndevelopers so if they have high emotional intelligence, this will impact on all\nthe team; because their position in the project always we be the center of the\nwork and their role is the most effective on the process. The next section we\nwill talk about the “Leadership and emotional intelligence” and how will impact\nthe success or the failure of the process. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>D.&nbsp;&nbsp; Leadership and Emotional Intelligence</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Goleman\nstates “Gifted leadership occurs where heart and head - feeling and thought -\nmeet.” [19]. When you compare the founders of Apple Steve Wozniak and Steve\nJobs you will find a lot of differences between them, Steve Wozniak will\nforever be remembered as one of the greatest hardware engineers of all time, he\nsingle-handedly created the Apple I. On the other hand, we have Steve Jobs was\ntalented in many fields such as User Interface (UI) and User Experience (UX)\nalso he has the ability to build teams and achieving goals, but can we say the\njobs have more emotional intelligence than Wozniak [23]. Actually, we can\'t say\nthis, unless we will define how we will measure the impact of both of them on\ntheir teams. In this section, we will see how emotional intelligence affects\nleadership and how the leader has to develop emotional intelligence as a skill\nto be a successful leader, from team\'s leaders to project manager to famous Chief\nexecutive officers.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>E.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impact of Emotional intelligence on Team Leaders</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A team leader is\na person who provides direction, instructions, and guidance for his team.\nUsually, this role can be assigned for the most skilled and experienced\ndevelopers, because of this narrative teams can face a lot of issues if the\nleader doesn\'t have the qualification of a leader. From the main qualifications\nwe mentioned in the section about senior developers is the “emotional\nintelligence”, leaders need skills like self-management, social awareness,\nself- awareness and&nbsp; relationship\nmanagement, his main job is to build a strategy for his team to reach their\ngoals, and provide any training his team members needs and communicate and\nListen to team members\' feedback also monitor team members\' participation to\nensure the training they are being provided is being put into use, and also to\nsee if any additional training is needed and manage the flow of day-to-day\noperations, because of this team leader have to acquire emotional intelligence\nto perform well and be successful leader. The strength of the emotional\nqualities of the leader, the ability to communicate and to establish\ninterpersonal relationships, the ability to create a friendly, motivating\nenvironment, are traits that distinguish leaders with outstanding economic\nperformance (so-called \"star-leaders\") from leaders with mediocre\nresults [21].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>F.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Impact of Emotional intelligence on Project Manager</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>One important lesson that managers may\nlearn from the study of emotional intelligence is that “emotional intelligence\nexists in all ages, genders, and races...how and when it will be used depends\non the individuals” [5]. The role of a project manager is client representative\nand has to determine and implement the exact needs of the client, based on\nknowledge of the organization they are representing. In software development\nthis role has more impact than the team leader, the team leader has to deal\nwith his team issue and some technical issue, on the other hand, the project\nmanager has to deal with client and all teams issues. Several studies have\nhighlighted the essential qualities and skills of IS project managers to ensure\nsuccess, highlight the importance of IS manager’s ability to manage people,\ntechnology, stress, emotions, organizational bureaucracy, and communication\n[1].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Project Managers need to influence,\nnegotiate, and collaborate with other departments and teams for resources and\nto understand project dependencies, the ability to build relationships and\nunderstand how to get the best from others, these skills are essential for any\nsuccessful project manager. Also, the successful project manager knows how to\nbuild effective teams - people always are key to the success of any project,\nand they have to empower them and understand them and their emotions.&nbsp; As we said project manager deals with clients\nand teams so he must have the ability to know their emotions and reflect with\nthe right decision, for example, if he finds a qualified leader in teams he\nshould give him an opportunity to lead people on the project and use\nmicromanagement with him. On the client\'s side project manager has to deliver\nthe best solution for them and understand what they want and this can\'t be\nachieved unless the project manager has a high emotional intelligence. One\nmanager blows up a group picture of a high-achieving team each quarter and\nhangs it, poster style, outside his office, a tribute to the developer as a\nhero, this is an indicator that tells you this manager have a high emotional\nintelligence [3]. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>G.&nbsp;&nbsp; Impact of Emotional intelligence in CEOs</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>From the first\nexample in this section talked about Jobs and Wozniak, from this paragraph\neveryone will say yes, Jobs have more emotional intelligence than Wozniak\nbecause he was more successful and his skills with building teams lead apple to\nbe the only company on the earth have more than one trillion-dollar evaluation.\nMaybe in this paper we will disagree with this opinion, Jobs have very good\nemotional intelligence but he has it in a different field on a different category,\nthe next level on emotional intelligence is “how to understand your customer?”\nevery company try to make technology and make people using it to prove that is\nsuccessful, on the other hand, Jobs started from what people want from\ntechnologies, this is an indicator that Jobs was very good listener to his\nusers and customers; their feelings; their emotions.&nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Emotional\nintelligence can become a multiplier factor of the revenue of a company with\nmillions of dollars. But, as the emotional qualities create a precise value\n[21].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>According to the\nanalysis, a company’s climate, how people feel, is responsible for 20% -30% of\nthe business performances of the company concerned. And the climate is\ndetermined at a rate of 50% -70% by one person: the leader is the one who\ncreates the conditions that lead directly to people\'s ability to work with gain\n[24]</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Lack of emotional\nqualities at the top level management causes considerable losses both to\nprivate companies and state institutions. Often these losses are overlooked or\nare mistakenly placed on other, short-term, more visible factors. Therefore, we\nneed an awareness of the importance of the emotional component of leadership\nwhich lead to greater levels of emotional intelligence in the management\nsector, where strategic decisions are taken [21].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>H.&nbsp;&nbsp; Team Building Techniques</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>There are two\ntype of teams in today’s companies, teams you didn\'t choose to work with; especially\nif you are working with big company or government institutions, and teams you\ncan create by yourself; like small business and startups, in this section we\ntalk about team building and team formation and know how the process is\nexecuted.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>1)&nbsp;&nbsp; History and Regular Techniques in Team Formation &nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Team formation\nprocess in essential for every companies that have project, project manager\nassign the assign group of employee to make a team and assign one of them to be\nthe team leader, it can be more flexible for the team leader to choose his team\nby person, from this point of view we can say that this job is the responsibility\nfor project manager or team leader. To build a team the leader will structure\nthe team depend on two main concepts: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Size of the team.</li><li>Roles or positions. </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>So in the\nbeginning he will decide who will the size of the team and then he will assign\nroles for each team member. For example, in regular development team split by\nskills set so we will have:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>1-2 Front-End\n     Developers.</li><li>1-2 Back-End Developers.</li><li>1 UI/UX Designer.</li><li>1 QA Specialist.</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>On the other\nhand, there is formation don\'t have any specific skills such as big team of\ndeveloper working on C++ algorithms, everyone can do the tasks, also there is a\nformation for R&amp;D (research and development)&nbsp;teams:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Team for Everything </li><li>Goal-Focused Squad </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are some\nbasic formation for team formation and building in software development. The\nproblem with these techniques is “no one looks at the resources as people”;\nbecause of these regular formations, team conflict will appear between team\nmembers, maybe their personalities are different, maybe they will not fit with\neach other. These are a small detail can lead to issues may influence the project\nand the company itself. &nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To decrease the\nprobability for these issue we will propose a method to give you another look\nin the depth of creating teams. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>I.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; MBTI and Personalities; What\nis MBTI?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Myers–Briggs\nType Indicator (MBTI) is an introspective self-report questionnaire with the\npurpose of indicating differing psychological preferences in how people\nperceive the world around them and make decisions. it was constructed by\nKatharine Cook Briggs and her daughter Isabel Briggs Myers. It is based on the\nconceptual theory proposed by Carl Jung, who had speculated that humans\nexperience the world using four principal psychological functions – sensation,\nintuition, feeling, and thinking – and that one of these four functions is\ndominant for a person most of the time [6].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The essence of\nthe theory is that much seemingly random variation in the behavior is actually\nquite orderly and consistent, being due to basic differences in the ways\nindividuals prefer to use their perception and judgment. \"Perception\ninvolves all the ways of becoming aware of things, people, happenings, or\nideas. Judgment involves all the ways of coming to conclusions about what has\nbeen perceived. If people differ systematically in what they perceive and in\nhow they reach conclusions, then it is only reasonable for them to differ\ncorrespondingly in their interests, reactions, values, motivations, and\nskills.\" In developing the Myers-Briggs Type Indicator instrument, the aim\nof Isabel Briggs Myers, and her mother, Katharine Briggs, was to make the\ninsights of type theory accessible to individuals and groups. They addressed\nthe two related goals in the developments and application of the MBTI\ninstrument [6]:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The identification of\n     basic preferences of each of the four dichotomies specified or implicit in\n     Jung\'s theory.</li><li>The identification and\n     description of the 16 distinctive personality types that result from the\n     interactions among the preferences”</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>J.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; What is the MBTI Personality Test?</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>It is a\nmeasurement tool for the personality type: <strong>Mind</strong>, <strong>Energy</strong>, <strong>Nature</strong>,\n<strong>Tactics</strong> and <strong>Identity</strong>. Each of these aspects should be seen as a\ntwo-sided continuum, with the “neutral” option placed in the middle. Starting\nwith <strong>Mind </strong>there is an <strong>introverted </strong>individuals prefer solitary\nactivities and get exhausted by social interaction. They tend to be quite\nsensitive to external stimulation (e.g. sound, sight or smell) in general. And <strong>Extraverted\n</strong>individuals prefer group activities and get energized by social\ninteraction. They tend to be more enthusiastic and more easily excited than\nintroverts. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For <strong>Energy </strong>there\nis <strong>Observant </strong>individuals are highly practical, pragmatic and\ndown-to-earth. They tend to have strong habits and focus on what is happening\nor has already happened. And <strong>Intuitive </strong>individuals are very imaginative,\nopen-minded and curious. They prefer novelty over stability and focus on hidden\nmeanings and future possibilities.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For <strong>Nature,\nthinking </strong>individuals focus on objectivity and rationality, prioritizing\nlogic over emotions. They tend to hide their feelings and see efficiency as\nmore important than cooperation. And <strong>Feeling </strong>individuals are sensitive\nand emotionally expressive. They are more empathic and less competitive than\nThinking types, and focus on social harmony and cooperation. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For <strong>Tactics</strong>,\n<strong>judging </strong>individuals are decisive, thorough and highly organized. They\nvalue clarity, predictability and closure, preferring structure and planning to\nspontaneity. And <strong>Prospecting </strong>individuals are very good at improvising\nand spotting opportunities. They tend to be flexible, relaxed nonconformists\nwho prefer keeping their options open. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>For <strong>Identity,\nAssertive </strong>(-A) individuals are self-assured, even-tempered and resistant to\nstress. They refuse to worry too much and do not push themselves too hard when\nit comes to achieving goals. And <strong>Turbulent </strong>(-T) individuals are\nself-conscious and sensitive to stress. They are likely to experience a wide\nrange of emotions and to be success-driven, perfectionistic and eager to\nimprove [6].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>These are the aspect that the test builds on it,\nthese test contain 36 question with ordinal scale.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>K.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Personality Types [7]</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>1)&nbsp;&nbsp; Architect Personality (INTJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This type defined\nby their confidence, logic, and exceptional decision-making, but all of this\nhides a turbulent underbelly – their emotions. The very notion of emotional\nexpression is synonymous with irrationality and weakness to many Architects, a\ndisplay of poor self-governance and fleeting opinion that can hardly stand up\nto the enduring light of factual truth.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2)&nbsp;&nbsp; Logician Personality (INTP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>This type defined\nby love patterns, and spotting discrepancies between statements could almost be\ndescribed as a hobby, making it a bad idea to lie to a Logician. This makes it\nironic that Logicians’ word should always be taken with a grain of salt – it’s\nnot that they are dishonest, but people with the Logician personality type tend\nto share thoughts that are not fully developed, using others as a sounding\nboard for ideas and theories in a debate against themselves rather than as\nactual conversation partners.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>3)&nbsp;&nbsp; Commander Personality (ENTJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Commanders are\nnatural-born leaders. People with this personality type embody the gifts of\ncharisma and confidence, and project authority in a way that draws crowds\ntogether behind a common goal. However, Commanders are also characterized by an\noften ruthless level of rationality, using their drive, determination and sharp\nminds to achieve whatever end they’ve set for themselves. Perhaps it is best that\nthey make up only three percent of the population, lest they overwhelm the more\nsensitive personality types that make up much of the rest of the world – but we\nhave Commanders to thank for many of the businesses and institutions we take\nfor granted every day.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>4)&nbsp;&nbsp; Debater Personality (ENTP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Debater\npersonality type is the ultimate devil’s advocate, thriving on the process of\nshredding arguments and beliefs and letting the ribbons drift in the wind for\nall to see. Debaters don’t do this because they are trying to achieve some\ndeeper purpose or strategic goal, but for the simple reason that it’s fun. No\none loves the process of mental sparring more than Debaters, as it gives them a\nchance to exercise their effortlessly quick wit, broad accumulated knowledge\nbase, and capacity for connecting disparate ideas to prove their points.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>5)&nbsp;&nbsp; Advocate Personality (INFJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Advocate\npersonality type is very rare, making up less than one percent of the\npopulation, but they nonetheless leave their mark on the world. As members of\nthe Diplomat Role group, Advocates have an inborn sense of idealism and\nmorality, but what sets them apart is that they are not idle dreamers, but\npeople capable of taking concrete steps to realize their goals and make a\nlasting positive impact.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>6)&nbsp;&nbsp; Mediator Personality (INFP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Mediator\npersonalities are true idealists, always looking for the hint of good in even\nthe worst of people and events, searching for ways to make things better. While\nthey may be perceived as calm, reserved, or even shy, Mediators have an inner\nflame and passion that can truly shine. Comprising just 4% of the population,\nthe risk of feeling misunderstood is unfortunately high for the Mediator\npersonality type – but when they find like-minded people to spend their time\nwith, the harmony they feel will be a fountain of joy and inspiration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>7)&nbsp;&nbsp; Protagonist Personality (ENFJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Protagonists are\nnatural-born leaders, full of passion and charisma. Forming around two percent\nof the population, they are oftentimes our politicians, our coaches and our\nteachers, reaching out and inspiring others to achieve and to do good in the\nworld. With a natural confidence that begets influence, Protagonists take a\ngreat deal of pride and joy in guiding others to work together to improve\nthemselves and their community.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>8)&nbsp;&nbsp; Campaigner Personality (ENFP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Campaigner\npersonality is a true free spirit. They are often the life of the party, but\nunlike types in the Explorer Role group, Campaigners are less interested in the\nsheer excitement and pleasure of the moment than they are in enjoying the\nsocial and emotional connections they make with others. Charming, independent,\nenergetic and compassionate, the 7% of the population that they comprise can\ncertainly be felt in any crowd.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>9)&nbsp;&nbsp; Logistician Personality (ISTJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Logistician\npersonality type is thought to be the most abundant, making up around 13% of\nthe population. Their defining characteristics of integrity, practical logic\nand tireless dedication to duty make Logisticians a vital core to many\nfamilies, as well as organizations that uphold traditions, rules and standards,\nsuch as law offices, regulatory bodies and military. People with the\nLogistician personality type enjoy taking responsibility for their actions, and\ntake pride in the work they do – when working towards a goal, Logisticians hold\nback none of their time and energy completing each relevant task with accuracy\nand patience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>10)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Defender Personality (ISFJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Defender\npersonality type is quite unique, as many of their qualities defy the\ndefinition of their individual traits. Though sensitive, Defenders have\nexcellent analytical abilities; though reserved, they have well-developed\npeople skills and robust social relationships; and though they are generally a\nconservative type, Defenders are often receptive to change and new ideas. As\nwith so many things, people with the Defender personality type are more than\nthe sum of their parts, and it is the way they use these strengths that defines\nwho they are.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>11)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Executive Personality (ESTJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Executives are\nrepresentatives of tradition and order, utilizing their understanding of what\nis right, wrong and socially acceptable to bring families and communities\ntogether. Embracing the values of honesty, dedication and dignity, people with\nthe Executive personality type are valued for their clear advice and guidance,\nand they happily lead the way on difficult paths. Taking pride in bringing\npeople together, Executives often take on roles as community organizers,\nworking hard to bring everyone together in celebration of cherished local\nevents, or in defense of the traditional values that hold families and\ncommunities together.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>12)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Consul Personality (ESFJ):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>People who share\nthe Consul personality type are, for lack of a better word, popular – which\nmakes sense, given that it is also a very common personality type, making up\ntwelve percent of the population. In high school, Consuls are the cheerleaders\nand the quarterbacks, setting the tone, taking the spotlight and leading their\nteams forward to victory and fame. Later in life, Consuls continue to enjoy\nsupporting their friends and loved ones, organizing social gatherings and doing\ntheir best to make sure everyone is happy.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>13)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Virtuoso Personality (ISTP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Virtuosos love to\nexplore with their hands and their eyes, touching and examining the world\naround them with cool rationalism and spirited curiosity. People with this\npersonality type are natural Makers, moving from project to project, building\nthe useful and the superfluous for the fun of it, and learning from their\nenvironment as they go. Often mechanics and engineers, Virtuosos find no\ngreater joy than in getting their hands dirty pulling things apart and putting\nthem back together, just a little bit better than they were before.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>14)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adventurer Personality (ISFP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Adventurer personalities\nare true artists, but not necessarily in the typical sense where they’re out\npainting happy little trees. Often enough though, they are perfectly capable of\nthis. Rather, it’s that they use aesthetics, design and even their choices and\nactions to push the limits of social convention. Adventurers enjoy upsetting\ntraditional expectations with experiments in beauty and behavior – chances are;\nthey’ve expressed more than once the phrase “Don’t box me in!”.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>15)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entrepreneur Personality (ESTP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Entrepreneurs\nalways have an impact on their immediate surroundings – the best way to spot\nthem at a party is to look for the whirling eddy of people flitting about them\nas they move from group to group. Laughing and entertaining with a blunt and\nearthy humor, Entrepreneur personalities love to be the center of attention. If\nan audience member is asked to come on stage, Entrepreneurs volunteer – or\nvolunteer a shy friend.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>16)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Entertainer Personality (ESFP):</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Entertainers get\ncaught up in the excitement of the moment and want everyone else to feel that\nway, too. No other personality type is as generous with their time and energy\nas Entertainers when it comes to encouraging others, and no other personality\ntype does it with such irresistible style.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nIV.&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>&nbsp;DISCUSSION </strong><strong></strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>A.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Team Formation Using MBTI; Proposed\nSolution &amp; Implementation </h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After we have\ndefined personalities types according to Myers–Briggs Type Indicator (MBTI) we\nwill propose the solution that will help team leaders and project manager with\nteam formation and building and pay attention to personalities types before\ncreating teams.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Solution has\ntwo steps:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>The team should take the personalities test online and\n     get the results [25]. Also, we have mentioned in the conclusion that we\n     will make a customized version for a software developer to make the test\n     more realistic to IT field only.</li><li>After the result team leader will analyze the best\n     formation depend on their personality, we will take examples and use cases\n     from real life project and teams in the next section </li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The solution can\ngive team leader another specification about the members, their strengths and\nweaknesses, their emotions and how can he create the team with a strong\nstructure. For the project manager, he will have overall look to the teams and\nthe team leaders and know the similarities of the conflict can be happening\nbetween these individuals.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>1)&nbsp;&nbsp; MPTI Team Formation Use Case in Scrum</h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Scrum is a\nframework within which people can address complex adaptive problems, while\nproductively and creatively delivering products of the highest possible value,\nThe Scrum Team consists of a <strong>Product Owner</strong>, the <strong>Development Team</strong>,\nand a <strong>Scrum Master</strong>. Scrum Teams are self-organizing and\ncross-functional. Self-organizing teams choose how best to accomplish their\nwork, rather than being directed by others outside the team. Cross-functional\nteams have all competencies needed to accomplish the work without depending on\nothers not part of the team. The team model in Scrum is designed to optimize\nflexibility, creativity, and productivity. The Scrum Team has proven itself to\nbe increasingly effective for all the earlier stated uses, and any complex work\n[26].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In if you are a\nproject manager and have 5 members and you want to create a scrum team with\nproduct owner and scrum master and development team, we will assume that all\nthe team members have the same experienced and you are new project manager,\nalso these are the results of the test: ENTJ, ESFP, INFP, ISFP, ESTJ. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The team\nformation will be like this:</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>INFP (product owner) because this person is idealistic\n     and searches for completeness, it will help the product to be ideal and\n     complete without bugs of issues.</li><li>ENTJ vs ESTJ (will be the scrum master) in the case of\n     ENTJ the project must be strict and the team with experienced because\n     these type of personalities looking for results and don\'t care about the\n     mistakes, and we choose ESTJ if the project is new and there is no strict\n     deadline; because of this personality help with creating a good\n     environment with team member and make them comfortable.</li><li>ESFP, ISFP can be good team member both these\n     personalities are helpful and can fit with any personality, on the other\n     hand, we can assign ISFP to spark solution in a scrum because these\n     personalities love the adventures and it can be used to test and try a new\n     thing to estimate spark solution [26].</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":3} -->\n<h3>2)&nbsp;&nbsp; MPTI Team Formation Use Case in Pair Programming </h3>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Pair programming\nis an agile software development technique in which two programmers work\ntogether at one workstation. One, the driver, writes code while the other, the\nobserver or navigator, reviews each line of code as it is typed in. The two\nprogrammers switch roles frequently [27].</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Let\'s assume that\nwe have a team in a company, contains three seniors and two junior developers\nand the team leaders want to adopt PP as techniques to improve the junior\'s\nskills such as Clean Code, Fast writing, research and problem-solving. On the\nother hand, he wants his senior developers to improve the mentorship skills and\nhelping the others. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also, let\'s\nassume they have these personalities: </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>Junior\n     developers (ESFP, ISFP)</li><li>Senior\n     developers (ENTJ, ENFP, INFP)</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Using MBTI\npersonalities type we have a pre-defined view for every member in the team,\nthree of the seniors have (N) in their personalities, that means we can assign\nthem as a leader, but how can we choose the best two from them to work with\njunior developers using pair programming?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The answer is\n(ENFP, INFP); because they have (P) and not (J), ENTJ have a lot of conflict\nwith all personalities that have (P), and it can be harmful to these juniors to\nwork with such as senior using pair programming, also this type of development\ntechniques need a lot of patients and both ENFP and INFP have this in their\npersonalities.&nbsp;&nbsp; </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>B.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Advantages for using this technique</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>1-\nKnow your team before start work with them;</strong><strong> these results tell you a lot about how each member\nof your team likes to work and with whom they will collaborate most effectively\nand efficiently or not. Before leaders should start putting teams together,\nthey should make sure their personality types don’t clash, and strengths and\nweaknesses complement one another.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>2- Improve communication;</strong><strong> if the teams know their personalities type and the\nothers this will improve the communication part and increases the understanding\nbetween each other, and find the best ways to communicate with one another. On\nthe leader side, he will have the perfect getaway to communicate with each\nmember of the team.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>3- Reduce conflict and improve the\nproductivity;</strong><strong> every great\nleader always put the right person on the right place, when leader know the\nweakness and the strength of all team member, he can assign them to roles that\ntake into account those difference, this can reduce the conflict between the\nroles and the team member and increase their productivity and efficiency.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>4- Motivate every member in the team;</strong><strong> when the leader knows about all his team member\nsome information such as personalities type, he can use this information to\ndiscover more about these individuals especially the motivation, everyone in life\nhas his own reasons or motivation to work, leaders can use these reasons to\nmotivate their team members and encourage them to improve more and more.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>5-Improve team member\'s skills; leaders can use MBTI\nresults to improve their team member\'s skill set, such as leadership,\nindividual skills like Art Skills, also this give the company the trust of any\nmember; because they care about his skills. </strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>6- Minimize Risks can threat projects by a\nteam member</strong><strong>; before team\nformation leader can look at all MBTI personalities for his team and choose\nwisely before assign anyone them; because there is a personality can conflict\nwith each other and these personalities can harm the project on the long-term\nand maybe will cause risks for the project itself.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>7- Develop a personal development plan for\neach member;</strong><strong> knowing such\ninformation about team member can help the leader to create a personal\ndevelopment plan for each or help them to create it.</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>8- Choose the right career path;</strong><strong> most employees don’t have the experience with choosing\nthe right carrier path, the leader can help them to choose if he knows\ninformation such personalities type.</strong><strong></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading -->\n<h2>C.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Disadvantages for using this technique</h2>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>1- <strong>Different\ntype of personalities and the accuracy</strong>; this information can be not real or\nfake and maybe the person doesn\'t provide this information correctly for a\nreason.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>2- <strong>Personalities\ncan be changed by time</strong>; this problem can happen because all human are\ngrowing creatures, so they don’t stay at one condition, their personalities may\nchange to other such as people with ENTJ can be changed to ENTP may be after\nshocking experience that may shake the judgmental mentality with (J).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>3- <strong>Experienced\ndevelopers and hierarchy in the company</strong>; this why using this technique can\ndamage teams in some situations, for example, if we have experienced developer\nin a team and he don’t have any leadership skill or personalities such as ENTJ,\nINTP, using MPTI team formation this developer can\'t be a team leader; because\nhe doesn’t have the qualification to be a team leader except that he has a lot\nof experience, in these situations this developer will be assigned as team\nleader and if not; he will not be a good team member if the team leader is less\nthan him with experienced and this can lead to conflict.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nV.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>CONCLUSION</strong><strong></strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To\nconclude, this paper tries to make a point in today\'s world about emotional\nintelligence in software development and propose a new model to help leaders in\nthe process of team formation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>At\nthe beginning of this paper, we demonstrate the importance of the emotional\nintelligence and how the big companies looking to it now, also how these\ncompanies will shape the recruiting industry around soft skills and emotional\nintelligence. After this, we clarified all definitions that related to\nemotional intelligence and start to understand the types and how to measure it?</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In\nthe second section we talked about the related work in such field, also we\nclarify if there any research correlate between emotional intelligence\nindicators and another topic such as leadership, teams, and stress on teams in\nsoftware development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In\nthe third section, we start to put the words together and analyze emotional\nintelligence in different situations in software development parts, such as\nteams, developers, leaders, project manager, and the higher management level.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also\nin the third section, we talked about the process of regular team formation and\nhow it happens, and we start to demonstrate the MBTI model and the test and how\nit works. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In\nthe fourth section, we have proposed the model that we suggest to work within\nthe team formation process. To create a great team, you should get the results\nof your team on MBTI test and analyze it before giving roles to everyone,\nleaders should get these data and use it to create their teams and assign roles.\nAlso, we mentioned in the same section the advantages and the disadvantages of\nthis model.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a\nconclusion, we can say this paper can help the leader to pay attention more in\nthe soft skills especially the emotional intelligence part for their teams and\nhighlight it throw the process of software development.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Also,\nwe hope to continue our future work to implement MBTI test personalities for IT\nfields only, with specific questions and use case from the software development\nprocess. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Finally,\nstudies conducting emotional intelligence training with university students\nshow a marked increase in emotional intelligence measured by a pre- and\npost-test measure [8], so yes everyone has an opportunity to teach himself and\nfind tools to help him to improve emotional intelligence.&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":1} -->\n<h1><strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\nVI.&nbsp;&nbsp; </strong><strong>Future work</strong></h1>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As\nfuture work for this paper, we will build an MBTI test customize for workers in\nsoftware development, such as developers, QA, Technical Support, help disk\n…etc.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>To\nbuild such as test; we will make a list of all questions that can give insights\nabout personalities, and all these questions should be related to IT jobs,\nthese question can be collected throw a survey with a group of workers in this\nfield or using focus groups.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The\nprocess of creating these question is the easy part, but to decide if the\nquestion can fit the MBTI test; this is the main challenge. To solve this, we\nhave to study more about the nature of the MBTI test especially the five type\nof personalities categories: Mind, Energy, Nature, Tactics, and Identity.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>After\nthis, we can test our MBTI test with a group of workers in the field and\ncompare the result with the same group with regular MBTI test and see if our\ntest has achieved more accurate results.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:heading {\"level\":5} -->\n<h5><strong>References</strong></h5>\n<!-- /wp:heading -->\n\n<!-- wp:list -->\n<ul><li>&nbsp;Leadership: A Critical\nSuccess Factor in IT Project Management, Mohan Thite,School of Organizational\nBehaviour &amp; Human Resource Management, Griffith University, Nathan,\nQueensland, Australia</li><li>Leadership That Gets Results, Daniel Goleman</li><li>What You Can Learn from the People Who Manage the People Who\nWrite Software, Monci J.Williams ,No. U9608A</li><li>Leadership dispersion as a function of performance in\ninformation systems teams, karin klenke, Leadership Development\nInstitute,Midlothian,Virginia</li><li>Emotional Intelligence Is Synergy in Intelligence, Mohammed R.\nAhmed ,Department of Management, p8.</li><li>MBTI basics, The Myers-Briggs Foundation, 2014, Retrieved 18\nJune 2014.</li><li>&nbsp;Myers-Briggs Type\nIndicator (MBTI), CPP.com, Menlo Park, CA, 2014, Retrieved 18 June 2014.</li><li>Ability-versus skill-based assessment of emotional intelligence,\nTravis R. Bradberry and Lac D. Su, page 61.</li><li>Apple, IBM, and Google don\'t care anymore if you went to college\n,Corinne Purtill , https://qz.com/work/1367191/apple-ibm-and-google-dont-require-a-college-degree/</li><li>Workforce connections,key &nbsp;“soft&nbsp; skills”&nbsp;\nthat&nbsp; foster&nbsp; youth &nbsp;workforce&nbsp; success:toward&nbsp; a&nbsp;\nconsensus &nbsp;across&nbsp;\nfields,june 2015,Laura H.Lippman,Renee Ryberg,Rachel Carney,Kristin\nA.Moore ,Child Trends</li><li>Soft skills for business success | Deloitte Australia | Deloitte\nAccess Economics, Human Capital John\nO’Mahony https://www2.deloitte.com/au/en/pages/economics/articles/soft-ski\nls-business-success.html</li><li>\"Google-interviews-harder-than-the-interviews\", <em>quora.com</em>,\n2018. [Online]. Available: https://www.quora.com/Are-Google-interviews-harder-than-the-interviews-of-Amazon-and-Microsoft.\n[Accessed: 10- Nov- 2018].</li><li>S. Bowkett, <em>Emotional intelligence</em>. London: Network\nContinuum Education, 2007.</li><li>Emotional Intelligence,John D. Mayer, Peter Salovey, David R.\nCaruso,and Lillia Cherkasskiy</li><li>Emotional intelligence,why it can matter more than iq,daniel\ngoleman</li><li>“EQ vs IQ,” <em>Mountain Bike vs Road Bike - Difference and\nComparison | Diffen</em>. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://www.diffen.com/difference/EQ_vs_IQ. [Accessed: 10-Nov-2018]. </li><li>\"IQ or EQ: Which One Is More Important?\", <em>Verywell\nMind</em>, 2018. [Online]. Available:\nhttps://www.verywellmind.com/iq-or-eq-which-one-is-more-important-2795287.\n[Accessed: 16- Nov- 2018].</li><li>Real Leaders Don\'t Follow, Don\'t Believe the Hype Around \'Emotional\nIntelligence,2018. [Online]. Available:\nwww.entrepreneur.com/article/237459&nbsp; [Accessed:\n16- Nov- 2018].</li><li>Article at Huffington Post 20 July [Online]:\nhttps://www.huffingtonpost.com/rita-balian-allen/emotional-intelligence-as_b_11072138.html\n. [Accessed: 16- Nov- 2018]. </li><li>G.Latha, N.Panchanatham, John William Felix from Annamalai\n&nbsp;University in India about \"Stress&nbsp;\nand&nbsp; Emotional&nbsp; Intelligence:&nbsp;\nA Study &nbsp;among&nbsp; Software&nbsp; Professionals&nbsp;\nin Chennai \".</li><li>“Emotional intelligence and leadership” by Suciu Sorin and\nVasile Gherhes form Polytechnic University of Timisoara]</li><li>Singing for Themselves By ALAN S. HOROWITZ SEPTEMBER</li><li>Who-was-more-important-Wozniak-or-Jobs,2018.[Online]. Available https://www.quora.com/Who-was-more-important-Wozniak-or-Jobs,\n[Accessed: 16- Nov- 2018].</li><li>McClelland, D. C. (1999), cf.\n&lt;https://www.talentsmart.com/media/ uploads/pdfs/ The_Business_\nCase_For_EQ.pdf&gt;.</li><li>16personalities,2018.[Online].Available\n&nbsp;https://www.16personalities.com/, [Accessed:\n16- Nov- 2018].</li><li>Scrum,2018.[Online].Available\n&nbsp;https://www.scrumguides.org/docs/scrumguide/v1/scrum-guide-us.pdf\n,[Accessed: 16- Nov- 2018].</li><li>Williams, Laurie (February 19–20, 2001). Ramsey, Dawn; Bourque,\nPierre; Dupuis, Robert, eds. <em>Integrating pair programming into a software\ndevelopment process</em>. 14th Conference on Software Engineering Education and\nTraining. Charlotte. pp. 27–36.</li><li>Salovey, Peter; Mayer, John; Caruso, David (2004),\n\"Emotional Intelligence: Theory, Findings, and Implications\", <em>Psychological\nInquiry</em>, pp. 197–215</li><li>Goleman, D. (1998). Working with emotional intelligence. New\nYork: Bantam Books</li><li>Petrides, K.V.; Pita, R.; Kokkinaki, F. (2007). \"The\nlocation of trait emotional intelligence in personality factor space\". <em>British\nJournal of Psychology</em>. <strong>98</strong> (2): 273–289.</li><li>Mayer, J.D.; Salovey, P.; Caruso, D.R.; Sitarenios, G. (2003).\n\"Measuring emotional intelligence with the MSCEIT V2.0\". <em>Emotion</em>.\n<strong>3</strong> (1): 97–105.</li><li>Mayer, John D (2008). \"Human Abilities: Emotional\nIntelligence\". <em>Annual Review of Psychology</em>. <strong>59</strong>: 507–536. </li><li>Petrides, K.V.; Furnham, A. (2003). \"Trait emotional\nintelligence: behavioral validation in two studies of emotion recognition and\nreactivity to mood induction\". <em>European Journal of Personality</em>. <strong>17</strong>:\n39–75</li></ul>\n<!-- /wp:list -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><br>\n</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->', 'Use Emotional Intelligence Indicators With Team Formation -Research Paper', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '9-revision-v1', '', '', '2019-06-13 14:18:15', '2019-06-13 13:18:15', '', 9, 'https://enghamzasalem.com/blog/index.php/2019/06/13/9-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
